Here's how to save and restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**In your ViewModel, also restore on initialization (cold start):**

```csharp
public class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set => SetProperty(ref _draftText, value);
    }

    public NoteViewModel()
    {
        // Restore any previously saved draft
        DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---------|----------|
| Save on background | `OnStopped` — fires when app is no longer visible |
| Restore on resume | `OnResumed` — fires when returning from background |
| Android back button | Also save in `OnDestroying` (skips `Stopped`) |
| Cold start | Restore in ViewModel constructor |
| Performance | `Preferences` is fast enough to avoid ANR/watchdog kills |

> **Note:** `OnResumed` does *not* fire on first launch — only after a `Stopped` state. That's why the constructor handles the cold-start restore.
